# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Key Learning Points
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8260-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Bronze Age was gradually replaced by the Iron Age in Britain approximately 2800 years ago."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.483781Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8260-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "This happened when iron working began to replace bronze manufacture."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.483786Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8260-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Iron is a common metal and is harder and tougher than bronze but harder to smelt as it requires very high temperatures."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.483790Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8260-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """At the time of this change, much of what is now England was inhabited by the Celtic people who had spread across Europe."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.483794Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8260-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Historians are not sure when they came to Britain or whether they did so peacefully."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.483798Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8256-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Neolithic Era saw lots of changes for early humans in Britain."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.484202Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8256-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Animal bones found during excavations suggest that this is when humans began to domesticate animals such as cattle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.484206Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8256-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This was the first time that people started deliberately planting and harvesting crops."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.484210Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8256-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Excavations at Skara Brae have unearthed barley seeds, suggesting cultivation."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.484214Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8256-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """New technologies developed: this is the first period from which archaeologists find pottery, including at Skara Brae."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.484218Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9524-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The River Nile remained the heart of the civilisation and was always highly important for the fertility it brought."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.485020Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9524-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The pharaohs ruled throughout this time, but where and how they were buried changed over time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.485024Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9524-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """While beliefs about the afterlife stayed the same, the methods of preserving bodies became very advanced over time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.485028Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9524-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Detailed hieroglyphs were used throughout, but gradually were used less and usually just for religious writings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.485032Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9524-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good description of how much things stayed the same will use knowledge from throughout this unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.485059Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8259-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Bronze was harder, longer lasting and could be made sharper than wood or stone tools."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.486874Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8259-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This meant that larger areas of wildwood could be cleared for agriculture and more crops could be planted."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.486878Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8259-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "This meant that a surplus could be traded or stored in case of disaster."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.486882Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8259-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Populations also grew as the land could support more people, who were needed for increased farming."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.486904Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8259-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists have found many examples of Bronze Age hoards in Britain. These hoards show how bronze was used."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.486908Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8262-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Large Iron Age hillforts, like at Castell Henllys and Maiden Castle, were built bigger than any previous settlement."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.486972Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8262-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is debated by historians whether these hillforts were for protection or to show off."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.486976Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8262-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The earthworks of some hillforts remain, and archaeologists have found lots of artefacts when digging them up."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.486980Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8262-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The potter’s wheel arrived in Britain allowing a greater range of quality pottery to be made."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.486984Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8262-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Coins were imported to Britain and modified, encouraging trade and shared values for goods."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.486987Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9519-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """On the 6 November 1922, an excavation in the Valley of the Kings led by Howard Carter discovered something incredible."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.487760Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9519-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """His team discovered a set of stone steps leading down a doorway covered in hieroglyphs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.487766Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9519-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Inside the doorway Carter could see a room filled with beautiful objects made from precious woods and metals."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.487770Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9519-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Howard Carter and his team had discovered the tomb of an Egyptian ruler called Tutankhamun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.487774Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9519-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """He was buried with objects as Egyptians believed he needed them in the afterlife and they wanted to show off his wealth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.487778Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9523-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Rosetta, some hundred years before Carter's discovery of Tutankhamun, some soldiers dug up a large black stone."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.487846Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9523-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It was covered in both Greek and hieroglyphic writing; archaeologists used the Greek to translate the hieroglyphs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.487850Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9523-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """These hieroglyphs were pictures, rather than words, and there were more than 1,000 of them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.487854Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9523-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Scribes would write in hieroglyphs to record things the pharaohs said or did and to compose religious messages."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.487858Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9523-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Over time scribes wanted to make hieroglyphs simpler and eventually they were only used for religious writings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.487862Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9526-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Mesopotamian civilisations like the Sumerians were able to trade their extra food with people who lived far away."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.597461Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9526-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists think that as these civilisations traded more they needed a way of recording what was being traded."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.597470Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9526-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They began to write down and count what they were giving and receiving in a special writing called cuneiform."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.597480Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9526-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Because their farming was productive, they could stay in one place, and so they built cities with large stone buildings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.597489Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9526-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some of the biggest of these stone buildings were called ziggurats, which were large, stepped religious buildings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.597499Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8261-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Iron farming tools like the ard plough could be used in heavy clay soils and wetter conditions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.598787Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8261-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This allowed a greater variety of crops to be grown, such as oats, and more land to become available for farming."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.598795Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8261-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Iron also allowed the creation of stronger tools, such as axes, meaning further clearing of the wildwood."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.598804Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8261-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """With more farming, the number of enclosed settlements grew and land ownership became more important."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.598813Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9525-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Around 3,000 years before Jesus was born, an ancient civilisation was flourishing between two large rivers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.599086Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9525-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It was called Sumer, and it sat between the Tigris and the Euphrates rivers in a place called Mesopotamia."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.599095Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9525-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """These rivers made it an ideal place to grow crops due to the soil being fertile, just like the Nile in Egypt."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.599109Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9525-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Sumerians did not just rely on the flooding of the rivers to make farming better."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.599118Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9525-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They built ditches and channels to divert water from the rivers to their fields, creating a reliable water supply."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.599126Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8258-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Bronze Age began nearly 4000 years ago in Britain."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.599266Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8258-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "This took place because many humans across the world began to make bronze."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.599275Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8258-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Bronze is made by melding the metals copper and tin to combine their properties."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.599284Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8258-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Bronze Age began at different points for different civilisations."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.599293Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8258-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Copper is common but tin less so; tin had to be traded to make bronze."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.599301Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9521-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The ruler of Ancient Egypt was called the pharaoh; they owned all the land, made all the laws and taxed their subjects."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.600183Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9521-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The pharaohs, whose subjects believed to be both gods and humans, ruled in the Old, Middle and New Kingdoms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.600192Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9521-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """During the Old Kingdom the Ancient Egyptians built pyramids to bury their pharaohs in, the most famous at Giza."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.600201Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9521-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In the Middle Kingdom Egypt grew rich and strong, stopped using pyramids and buried pharaohs in the Valley of the Kings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.600214Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9521-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In the New Kingdom Egypt grew stronger, using their chariots and strong bronze weapons to take over more land."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.600223Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9520-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """At one time there were two Egyptian kingdoms: Upper Egypt and Lower Egypt, but around 3,000 BCE they were united."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.600576Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9520-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The civilisation known as the Ancient Egyptians began over 3,000 years before the birth of Christ, 3,000 BC or BCE."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.600584Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9520-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They lived near a large river they called the Nile, in North Africa, protected from enemies by dry land to their sides."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.600593Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9520-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The River Nile was long, deep and filled with a dark black mud."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.600601Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9520-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When the Nile flooded, this mud made the land the Egyptians live on turn black, and become very fertile."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.600609Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8284-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Historians sometimes use criteria to judge the significance of events, developments or people’s actions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601013Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8284-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """These include: how many people were affected; how well remembered it has been; how long lasting the effects were."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601021Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8284-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Other criteria might be: how were people’s lives affected; who has been affected?"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601029Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8284-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good argument about the most significant legacy of Ancient Greece is likely to use some of these criteria."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601037Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8284-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good argument about the most significant legacy of Ancient Greece will use knowledge from across this unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601045Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8936-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Abbasid Caliphate overthrew the Umayyad Caliphate in 750 CE and ruled land from Tunis to Multan."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601132Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8936-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Baghdad was founded in 762 CE by caliph Al-Mansur to become the capital of the Abbasid Caliphate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601153Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8936-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Built by 100,000 workers to show off Abbasid wealth and power, it became the richest, most populous city in the world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601162Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8936-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "It was built on the fertile banks of the River Tigris in the Mesopotamia valley."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601170Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8936-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Baghdad had a circular layout and many public facilities like parks, hospitals, and libraries."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601178Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8957-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """World War One had many fronts; battles were fought on the Western Front, the Eastern Front, in Africa and in Asia."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601279Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8957-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Western Front saw the use of trench warfare where the conditions were terrible, and many people suffered."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601291Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8957-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In some battles, like the Somme in 1917, mass attacks led to thousands of dead or wounded soldiers in a day."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601300Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8957-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Many soldiers wrote letters or kept diaries to record their experiences."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601308Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9562-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Benin bronzes were produced in a place called Benin City, which was the heart of the Benin Kingdom."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601529Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9562-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Edo people built this city on a plain, which was known for the high mud walls and great ditches that enclosed it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601537Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9562-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Beyond the city walls roughly 500 separate villages were separated by further walls making up the suburbs of the city."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601545Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9562-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The city was well planned with straight roads and square houses and there were even metal palm oil burning street lamps."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601552Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9562-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Merchants and artisans worked and lived in the city, while farmers lived and worked in the surrounding rainforests."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601560Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9552-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "By the early 6th century, monasteries began to be set up across Ireland."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601607Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9552-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """At first, these were meant as places for Christians to retreat to and dedicate their lives to God."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601619Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9552-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They were often in remote, hard to reach places like the island of Skellig Michael."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601628Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9552-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many monasteries, though, attracted the patronage of kings and the rich and grew in both size and importance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601687Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9552-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They were centres for the teaching of poetry, literature, and the arts and produced manuscripts like the Book of Kells."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601696Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4621-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Like the Ancient Romans, whose beliefs had been influenced by the Ancient Greeks, the Celtic people were polytheistic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601743Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4621-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Britain, the Ancient Romans introduced their own gods and wiped out the druids (Celtic religious leaders) in 60CE."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601751Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4621-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Elsewhere the Ancient Romans were tolerant of Celtic religion, allowing it to continue alongside some of their gods."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601758Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4621-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Evidence shows us that religious change was slow, and often in combination with existing beliefs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601766Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9554-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Christianity survived the departure of the Romans in the places where the Anglo-Saxons did not settle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601774Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9554-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The main centre of this survival was Ireland, where Christianity grew more popular throughout the 5th century."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601782Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9554-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The importance of monasteries meant that Christianity flourished in Ireland."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601790Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9554-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The work of missionaries meant that Ireland began to spread Christianity to other places in the 6th century."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601797Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9554-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good explanation of why Christianity survived the Romans' departure will use knowledge from across this unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601809Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9778-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Britain needed workers to help with the nation's reconstruction and to work in the NHS; many came from the Caribbean."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601974Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9778-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The first of these arrived at Tilbury Docks on the 22 June 1948 after a long journey on the SS Empire Windrush."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601982Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9778-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some British people were very unwelcoming and many of these arrivals faced discrimination in housing and employment."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601989Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9778-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 1958, riots broke out in Notting Hill that were motivated by growing racial tension."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.601997Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9778-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Hundreds of white people attacked the homes of people from the Caribbean and the violence lasted two weeks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602004Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9543-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 1984, workers at a peat bog in North West England made an incredible discovery: the preserved body of a man."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602360Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9543-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists aren't sure exactly when he died, but it was some time around the end of the Iron Age in Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602368Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9543-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By looking at this preserved body, archaeologists have been able to work out all sorts of things about Iron Age Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602375Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9543-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """However, there are many questions that they still have about him and the time and society in which he lived."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602383Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9563-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Kingdom of Benin began in the 1000s CE and reached its peak in the 1400s CE under the rule of Oba Ewuare."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602390Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9563-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Obas were the rulers of Benin, and the people of Benin believed that they were divine and showed them great respect."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602403Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9563-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Anyone approaching the Oba did so on their knees and were not allowed to look at him without permission."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602411Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9563-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Oba lived in a palace where they would meet with their officials and lead religious ceremonies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602423Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9563-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The British Museum holds many brass wall plaques showing Obas with their attendants conducting these rituals."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602431Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9573-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Second World War broke out in 1939 when Nazi Germany invaded Poland."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602594Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9573-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Having promised to defend Poland, Britain and France declared war on Nazi Germany."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602602Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9573-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "When war was declared, many men and women joined the armed forces."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602610Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9573-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The war lasted six years and brought about significant changes for many people."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602617Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9573-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Second World War has been seen as a turning point because the changes it brought were decisive and permanent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602625Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8947-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 870, Wessex was ruled by the young king Aethelred, aided by his younger brother Alfred."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602676Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8947-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They managed to stall the Viking invasion of Wessex by defeating them at the Battle of Ashdown."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602684Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8947-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In further battles the Vikings pushed the forces of Wessex back, killing Aethelred in 871."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602691Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8947-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The new King Alfred fought against the Vikings, now reinforced by the Danish chief Guthrum who had arrived in 872."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602703Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8947-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Alfred made peace with the Vikings, probably bribing them, they went on to conquer Mercia and then Northumbria."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.602711Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9565-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In the 1500s CE Portugese merchants began to trade goods like guns with Benin in exchange for enslaved people."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603010Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9565-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Dutch, French and English entered this trade in the 1600s CE, making Benin rich and powerful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603018Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9565-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """However, by the 1800s CE, the power of Benin had weakened, and the British wanted to control trade in the region."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603025Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9565-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 1897 they invaded the kingdom of Benin, burning Benin City to the ground and making it part of British Nigeria."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603034Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9565-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """During the invasion thousands of pieces of Edo artwork, including some of those in the British Museum, were looted."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603041Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4620-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Despite the Ancient Romans' initial success in the south, other British Celts resisted the further Roman campaigns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603049Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4620-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """While some kings, like Caratacus, were crushed, others chose to become client rulers to avoid bloodshed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603056Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4620-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Boudica was the queen of the Iceni tribe in East Anglia; she rebelled and destroyed Colchester and London."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603064Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4620-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Boudica united with other tribes in southern England and outnumbered the Ancient Roman Legions that marched to meet her."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603072Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4620-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Despite her numerical advantage, Boudica's army was defeated by superior Ancient Roman tactics and her rebellion ended."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603080Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9567-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 1993 archaelogists discovered a magnificent tomb in the Honduran city complex of Copán."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603087Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9567-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Inside the tomb they found the remains of a person covered in red cinnabar and surrounded with shell and jade ornaments."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603095Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9567-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Around the human remains were burnt offerings of birds, turtles and fish."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603103Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9567-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Due to the things she was buried with the archaeologists think that these were the remains of an important woman."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603110Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9567-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """She was either a ruler, or the wife or mother of a ruler, of a group of people who lived at Copán called the Maya."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603118Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8916-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Christian Churches did not just emerge in the Western Roman Empire and the Byzantine Empire."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603353Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8916-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Aksum, an important trading kingdom near the Red Sea, Christianity became the dominant religion in the 4th century."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603362Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8916-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Sources such as coins, Ezana's stela and the Ezana Stone, suggest that this took place during the rule of King Ezana."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603369Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8916-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Ethiopia today, many Aksumite churches have been found carved into rocky mountainsides."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603377Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8916-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Inside these churches the walls are covered with beautiful paintings of Christian stories."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603384Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8269-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Greeks had many gods and goddesses and lots of stories and myths that surrounded them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603518Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8269-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Ancient Greeks believed in 12 major gods and goddesses who lived on Mount Olympus."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603526Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8269-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Greek Gods were associated with different things, e.g. Hera, Queen of the Gods, was associated with marriage and family."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603533Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8269-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The popular myth of Persephone and the Underworld shows us how the Ancient Greeks explained the change of the seasons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603541Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8269-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Another myth concerned the Moirai, the Fates, which suggests the Ancient Greeks believed in a type of natural order."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603548Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8941-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The caliphs paid scholars to come to the House of Wisdom to translate Greek, Persian and Indian texts into Arabic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603556Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8941-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They used these texts to create new knowledge that was spread throughout the Islamic world and even further afield."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603564Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8941-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Scholars translated the works of Greek and Roman doctors like Galen, saving and spreading this medical knowledge."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603572Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8941-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Scientists and scholars in Baghdad made many discoveries such as how lenses and the human eye work and making compasses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603579Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8941-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Geometrically patterned art looking like flowers and plants spread across the Muslim world from Baghdad."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603591Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9578-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """During the Second World War the experiences of men, women and children differed greatly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603902Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9578-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """However, the great changes that the Second World War brought about affected a large number of people."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603910Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9578-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Because of the global nature of the war British people were exposed to unfamiliar places, cultures and ways of life."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603917Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9578-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Second World War was a turning point for many women and for children because it changed their lives forever."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603925Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9578-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A strong explanation of why WWII was a turning point in many ways will reference knowledge from across this unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.603933Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4625-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The largest settlements built by the Celts were small hillforts."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604066Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4625-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Ancient Romans introduced towns, connected by roads across Britain."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604074Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4625-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Cirencester (Corinium Dobunnorum) was Roman Britain's second largest town."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604081Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4625-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Towns like Cirencester were designed in grids with the forum in the centre and some had aqueducts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604092Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4625-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some big towns like Cirencester had amphitheatres which were used for public entertainment."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604101Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8955-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Viking invasions caused huge amounts of conflict in Britain for over 200 years."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604108Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8955-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Viking trade brought valuable foreign goods to Britain and Viking settlement created new towns with Viking place names."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604116Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8955-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In areas of Viking settlement, Anglo-Saxons and Vikings often married, creating new generations with a mixed identity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604124Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8955-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The threat of the Vikings led to the Anglo-Saxons fortifying towns and gradually uniting their kingdoms to survive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604132Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8955-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good description of the ways in which Britain changed due to the Vikings will use knowledge from across this unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604140Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8914-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The early Christian Church that Constantine allowed was organised into Bishops, Presbyters and Deacons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604469Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8914-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Various councils were held over the years to agree on core beliefs like the three forms of God."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604477Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8914-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """After the establishment of Constantinople, Christianity in the Western Roman Empire developed in its own way."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604484Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8914-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Bishop of Rome, the Pope, was believed to have supremacy over the Christian Church as a whole."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604492Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8914-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Western Europe various monastic orders developed where the members devoted their life to God."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604500Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8940-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """One reason Al-Mansur planned Baghdad as a circle was his love of the Ancient Greek science of mathematics."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604543Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8940-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In the House of Wisdom, scholars translated Euclid’s book ‘The Elements’ and copies spread this knowledge in Europe."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604551Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8940-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In the late 8th century CE the Anglo Saxon King of Mercia, Offa either had a gold coin made, or it was made for him."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604559Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8940-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The coin, complete with Arabic script, is a copy of the golden dinars produced by Al Mansur, Offa’s contemporary."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604596Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8940-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It shows how important the golden dinar had become in the Mediterranean world due to the Abbasid domination of trade."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604605Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9764-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Despite fighting the Vikings and uniting the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms, Aetheflaed's story has often been forgotten."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604613Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9764-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """One possible reason for this is because her brother Edward wanted to make sure that Mercia stayed loyal to him."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604620Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9764-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Edward wanted Mercia to submit to him, and not stay loyal to his sister's memory."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604628Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9764-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is likely that Edward made sure that the Anglo-Saxon Chronicle mentioned a lot about him instead of Aethelflaed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604636Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9764-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Michael Wood is one historian who has tried to tell Aethelflaed's story because it is the story of England's beginning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604644Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8868-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Without the Roman legions to defend it, Germanic tribes invaded and quickly settled across Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604770Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8868-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "They established seven great Anglo-Saxon kingdoms that rivalled one another."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604778Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8868-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By the late 8th century Mercia was the most powerful kingdom following the rule of Offa and Cynethryth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604786Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8868-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Christianity withered away, but returned in the 6th and 7th centuries, eventually spreading across Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604794Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8868-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Scotland, the Picts were joined by Irish Scots who brought Gaelic culture with them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604801Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8867-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By 750 CE the kingdoms of Mercia, Wessex, Northumberland and East Anglia were the most powerful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604809Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8867-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By the second half of the 8th century, Mercia was ruled by King Offa and his Frankish queen, Cynethryth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604817Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8867-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Sometimes the most powerful Anglo-Saxon kings would claim to be the 'bretwalda', the ruler of all of Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604825Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8867-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Having won many battles against other Anglo-Saxon kingdoms, Offa called himself ‘bretwalda’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604833Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8867-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Offa was unable to defeat the Welsh; he built a barrier on his western borders to protect his kingdom against them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604840Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4626-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Many Celtic people adopted Ancient Roman ways of life, but some resisted."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604848Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4626-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ancient Roman religions were adopted in Britain but often overlapped with older beliefs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604860Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4626-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ancient Roman town building created major urban centres for the first time, connected by paved roads."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604872Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4626-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Roman settlement meant that people and goods from many countries travelled to Britain e.g. the Ivory Bangle Lady."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604881Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4626-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many aspects of life changed for people in Britain, and resistance to Ancient Roman rule and culture varied."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604889Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9551-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Although Christianity declined in Britain after the Romans left, it grew stronger in Ireland."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604897Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9551-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some people in Ireland had become Christian through contact with Roman Britain by the early 5th century."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604905Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9551-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The actions of the Roman-British missionary, St Patrick, some time in the 5th century, spread the religion more widely."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604912Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9551-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Risking martyrdom, he preached to the kings of north-east Ireland and set up churches."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604920Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9551-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """He recorded his life and missionary activities in his 'Confession' which is the main evidence we have for his life."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604928Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8865-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In places where the Anglo-Saxons defeated the Britons, they built their own villages and established new kingdoms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604935Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8865-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "No single king ruled over all the Anglo-Saxons."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604943Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8865-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Angles, Saxons and Jutes took over and settled in different areas."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604951Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8865-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Anglo-Saxons established seven kingdoms – Northumbria, Mercia, East Anglia, Essex, Kent, Sussex and Wessex."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604959Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8865-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "These kingdoms waxed and waned in their power over one another."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604966Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8939-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Baghdad was connected to Asia and the East through trade and exchanges of knowledge."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604974Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8939-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 771 CE, the Indian astronomer Kanaka came to Baghdad, bringing the Siddhanta, a book about maths and astronomy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604982Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8939-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Translating this text led to Arabic mathematicians adopting decimal numbers which spread across the medieval world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604990Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8939-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Muslim scholars used Greek ideas and the influence of the Siddhanta to build observatories and invent the astrolabe."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.604998Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8939-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Baghdad merchants traded with the Tang, making long journeys to Guangzhou to trade incense for jade, silk and ceramics."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605005Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9569-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In another Maya city, Yaxchilán, a carved stone lintel has helped archaeologists to understand a lot about Maya beliefs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605056Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9569-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It shows a bloodletting ritual performed by Yaxchilán's king, Shield Jaguar the Great, and his wife, Lady K’ab’al Xook."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605064Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9569-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Lady K’ab'al Xook pulled a thorned rope through her tongue to make it bleed so that she could speak with the gods."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605072Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9569-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Bloodletting was important to the Maya; they believed the gods had let their blood to create the human race."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605080Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9569-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By bloodletting, Maya rulers showed their thanks to the gods, but also showed that they were the right people to rule."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605087Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9777-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Before WWII, healthcare was not run by the government and varied greatly from place to place."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605095Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9777-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many people, especially women, were unable to afford healthcare and childhood illness was a big problem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605103Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9777-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Although the government ran schemes for workers to access free healthcare, this was mainly for men."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605110Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9777-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """During the war, the government took control of hospitals and this showed how much better things could be."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605125Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9777-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 1948, the National Health Service was set up offering free healthcare to everyone, improving the nation's health."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605134Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8937-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Baghdad was founded in the early days of Islamic civilisation’s ‘Golden Age’."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605327Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8937-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Islam spread from the Arabian peninsula to the Southern Mediterranean, Middle East and parts of Asia."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605334Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8937-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Islam spread due to strong leadership, military strength, opponents’ weaknesses and tolerance shown to captured cities."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605342Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8937-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The wealth that came from trading networks led to the founding of Baghdad as a new capital for the Abbassid Caliphate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605350Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8961-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Different towns, villages and areas helped to support the war effort by making certain things."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605380Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8961-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Historical buildings in pupils’ local areas may have been used to help support the war effort."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605393Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8961-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Streets and roads are often named after people who made a significant contribution to the war effort in some way."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605401Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8961-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The older generations within pupils’ families might have played a role in supporting the war effort on the Home Front."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605409Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8953-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 925, Edward’s son, Athelstan, was consecrated King of Mercia and Wessex with a crown: a new ceremony of coronation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605417Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8953-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 927, Athelstan captured the last Viking stronghold, York and began to mint coins bearing the title ‘rex Anglorum’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605424Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8953-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The north had not had a southern king; Athelstan assembled the rulers of Scotland and Northumbria to submit to him."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605432Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8953-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Welsh kings already recognised the overlordship of the King of Wessex."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605440Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8953-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Athelstan was now the overlord of all of Britain and some historians have called him the first ‘King of England’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605448Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9527-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Mesopotamia and the Nile were not the only places where people stopped moving around and settled down to farm."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605500Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9527-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Asia, other civilisations developed in the Indus River Valley and the Yellow River Valley."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605507Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9527-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Historians and archaeologists sometimes use the phrase 'cradles of civilisation' to describe these places."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605515Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9527-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """As in Egypt and Mesopotamia, the people of the Indus and the Yellow River Valleys channeled water for farming."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605523Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9527-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """As in Egypt and Mesopotamia, the people of the Indus and the Yellow River Valleys created cities and art."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605530Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8917-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Early Christians were persecuted in the Roman Empire, but under Constantine, the faith was encouraged and it spread."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605542Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8917-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The division of the Roman Empire led to slightly different Christian traditions in each part."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605551Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8917-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Byzantine Empire carried on after the fall of Rome, but did not recognise the Pope's supremacy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605559Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8917-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A separate Christian tradition also emerged in the African kingdom of Aksum."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605567Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8917-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good story about the way Christianity grew will use knowledge from across this unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605574Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4624-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Celtic buildings were usually thatched, wattle and daub roundhouses."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605825Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4624-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists can look at the remains of buildings to construct arguments about the impact of the Romans in Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605833Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4624-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Evidence of North African Roman soldiers has been found at Hadrian’s Wall, a major Ancient Roman architectural feature."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605841Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4624-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Caerwent, Trimontium and Bath are all places that have examples of the sorts of architecture the Ancient Romans built."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605848Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4624-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Rich Ancient Romans built villas in the British countryside with expensive mosaics and hypocaust systems for heating."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605856Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9568-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Maya lived in a part of central America called Mesoamerica."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605863Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9568-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Mesoamerica contained rich fertile lands in the highlands and plains, and humid rainforests in the lowlands."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605871Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9568-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """From about 750 BCE, the Maya built cities like Copán near rivers, just like other early civilisations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605879Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9568-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """These were all different, but usually contained a ceremonial centre with temple-pyramids, ballcourts  and palaces."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605887Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9568-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They often contained causeways and standing stones carved with pictures and writings about their rulers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605894Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9574-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Before the Second World War, women were expected to take care of domestic matters rather than working."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605902Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9574-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If women did work, they were mainly employed in shops, domestic service or nursing - jobs thought to be ‘women’s jobs’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605910Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9574-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In December 1941, women were conscripted for the first time in British history; they could now do ‘men’s jobs’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605917Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9574-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Women worked in munitions, aircraft and tank factories, in shipbuilding or farming."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605925Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9574-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Women also joined the armed forces as part of the WAAF, ATS or WRNS."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.605938Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8913-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By 312 CE, Constantine had become the emperor of the Western Roman Empire by defeating his rivals in many battles."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606052Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8913-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Before one of these battles he had a vision of a cross; he ordered his soldiers to paint crosses on their shields."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606060Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8913-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Constantine converted to Christianity, saying all religions could be practised and Christians should not be persecuted."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606067Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8913-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 324 CE, Constantine became sole emperor of the Roman Empire and in 330 CE created a new eastern capital."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606075Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8913-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 325 CE, Constantine brought together Christian bishops to try to agree the first set of rules about Christianity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606083Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8932-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Baghdad, the ‘City of Peace’, was a hugely important Islamic city for c. 500 years that grew with the spread of Islam."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606091Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8932-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Muslims believe Muhammad, a merchant from Mecca, became a prophet c. 610 CE by receiving revelations from Allah."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606098Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8932-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """These revelations were first spread orally and then written down in a single text known as the Qur’an."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606106Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8932-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The elites of Mecca rejected Muhammad’s revelations, forcing him to flee to escape persecution."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606118Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8932-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Hijra was the migration of the Prophet Muhammad and his followers from Mecca to Medina in 622 CE."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606126Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8208-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "At first to be Roman meant to be from the city of Rome."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606165Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8208-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To be a Roman was often associated with power and military strength."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606172Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8208-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The idea of how Rome should be ruled changed a lot over time."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606180Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8208-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Even when Rome fell, there was still a ‘Roman’ Empire in the East: the Byzantines."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606188Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8208-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good description of how ideas about what it meant to be Roman changed will use knowledge from across this unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606196Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8267-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The land around Athens was hard to farm. Athenians imported lots of food and built a seafaring trading society."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606523Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8267-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By 431 BCE the important city state of Athens was a democracy; Athenians debated and voted on laws in the Assembly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606531Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8267-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Men had duties; they had to obey the laws, serve in the army, help run the city, pay taxes and serve on juries."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606538Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8267-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Women were expected to stay at home and do housework; they cleaned, cooked and wove cloth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606545Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8267-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """About 100,000 enslaved people made up about a third of the population and almost every home had at least one."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606553Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9546-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 2001 in northern England, a grave was discovered of someone who must have been very important."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606560Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9546-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Inside the grave, alongside the bones, were the remains of an Iron Age chariot."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606567Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9546-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All that remained of the chariot were its metal parts and highly decorated bronze fittings, some inlaid with coral."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606578Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9546-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The grave therefore suggests that chariots were important in Celtic warfare in Britain during the Iron Age."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606585Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9546-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When the Romans came to Britain for the first time in the 1st century BCE, they noted that the Celts used chariots."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606593Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9564-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some of the objects held by the British Museum can tell us about the Edo's religious beliefs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606600Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9564-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """One brass statue is a head, decorated with animals, that was used during worship of the god Osun."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606607Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9564-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Osun was the Edo god of medicine and magic and was believed to command the animals of the rainforest."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606615Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9564-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The head represents how the Oba was believed to have magic powers like the gods; the birds represent prophesy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606622Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9564-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The snakes represent Osun's soldiers and the Oba's ability to use magic to destroy his enemies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606629Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8908-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """During the wars between Greece and Persia the north-eastern Greek kingdom of Macedon had ended up under Persian control."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606636Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8908-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Eventually the Greeks of Macedon pushed the Persians out and Alexander's father, Philip came to rule as King of Macedon."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606644Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8908-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Philip built Macedon into a powerful kingdom, convincing other city-states to join him, creating the League of Corinth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606655Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8908-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Philip created the League of Corinth to defeat Persia once and for all, but he was murdered before he could achieve it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606663Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8908-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Philip's son Alexander, tutored by Aristotle from Athens, was now King of Macedon and led Greece against Persia."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606670Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8871-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All the coins found at Sutton Hoo were Frankish, showing how well connected Kent and East Anglia were to Europe."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606747Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8871-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Roman influence continued: Offa made coins making him look like an Emperor with Romulus, Remus and a wolf on the back!"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606755Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8871-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Whilst major towns collapsed after the Romans left, evidence of coins suggested they grew again under the Anglo-Saxons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606766Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8871-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Anglo-Saxon kings such as Offa began to mint their own coins at growing towns in places like London and Canterbury."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606773Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8871-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """These, along with lots of pottery, show how towns grew due to the increasing wealth and trade in Anglo-Saxon Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606781Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8911-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """'The Great' is not a title that Alexander had during his lifetime; it is an epithet, given to him after his death."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606824Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8911-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Ancient Romans, who grew in power some time after Alexander, admired his achievements and used this epithet for him."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606831Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8911-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Alexander is remembered as 'Great' due to his military prowess: never losing a battle and personally leading his men."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606838Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8911-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """He has also been named 'The Great' for managing to keep his vast empire united, although it fragmented after his death."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606845Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8911-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In founding Alexandria, which went on to become a hugely important centre of learning, he has also been seen as 'Great'."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606856Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9530-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All of these early civilisations left a nomadic lifestyle because they found ways of farming fertile ground near rivers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606867Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9530-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All of them built permanent places to live like cities, along with other buildings for the purpose of religion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606875Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9530-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All of these early civilisations traded with people from far away and developed their own forms of writing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606882Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9530-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All of these early civilisations made bronze and used this metal for tools, weapons and artwork."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606889Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9530-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Despite all these similarities, all of these early civilisations had different styles of writing, building and art."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606897Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9558-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """York was a major centre for Viking trade and goods flowed in from across Europe and the Middle East."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606904Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9558-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The remains of silk were found in Coppergate, which likely originated from the Middle East."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606911Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9558-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is likely that silk, along with spices and gemstones like carnelian, came to York via Viking traders in Russia."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606918Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9558-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Baltic amber was used for jewellery in York, and, although no furs survive, it is likely that they were also traded."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606926Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9558-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An Arabic coin and a cowrie shell from the Red Sea or the Gulf of Aden are further proof of wide trade links."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.606933Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4617-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Roman senators overthrew the last King of Rome, creating the Roman Republic."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607058Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4617-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An important part of early Roman identity was the role of the senate in representing the wishes of the people."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607065Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4617-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Punic Wars were fought between Rome and Carthage and made Rome the dominant force in the Mediterranean."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607073Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4617-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 146 BCE, the Roman Republic made Macedonia a province and brought the Greek city-states under its control."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607080Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4617-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Not everyone in the Roman Republic was free (slavery was an important institution) or even a Roman citizen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607087Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4619-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Emperor Claudius ordered the invasion of Britain in 43 CE to secure his position as emperor."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607095Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4619-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The invasion was very successful due to the strengths of the Ancient Roman army."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607102Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4619-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ancient Roman legionaries were highly trained, well equipped and disciplined soldiers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607110Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4619-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The legionaries used superior tactics alongside fort building to defeat the British tribes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607117Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9560-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Lots of artefacts have been found in the Coppergate area that date from the time the Vikings lived there."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607158Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9560-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """These tell historians a lot about the buildings that were there and the activities that took place."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607165Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9560-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They show that Viking York was a major trading hub where goods came to from all over Europe, Asia and the Middle East."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607172Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9560-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many artefacts provide an insight into the daily lives of the Vikings who lived in York."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607179Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9560-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good explanation of how we know so much will describe various artefacts and what archaeologists have learnt from them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607187Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8958-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are many memorial sites around Britain where those who lost their lives in WWI are remembered."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607194Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8958-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "These memorials take many forms but they are most commonly large crosses."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607201Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8958-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Memorial ceremonies are commonly held at these sites on or near to Remembrance Day."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607209Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8958-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The 11th November is called 'Remembrance Day' because WWI officially ended at 11am on 11.11.1918."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607216Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8958-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Poppies are a symbol of remembrance because poppies grew in the fields in which soldiers lost their lives."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607223Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8281-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The first Olympic Games were held at Olympia in 776 BCE in honour of the gods and as part of a wider religious festival."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607279Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8281-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ancient Greeks believed that they would offend the Gods if they were to cheat in the Games."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607287Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8281-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Images on Ancient Greek pottery show us the sports that comprised the ancient Games and that only men could compete."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607295Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8281-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The ancient Olympic Games have left a lasting legacy in the form of the modern Olympic Games."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607302Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8281-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are similarities and differences between the ancient and modern Olympic Games."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607309Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8906-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Mesopotamia, where Sumer had once flourished, warring city-states continued to vie for supremacy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607320Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8906-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cyrus, king of Persian Achaemenids, conquered the kingdom of Medes and the city of Babylon, creating the Persian Empire."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607328Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8906-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cyrus' son Cambyses went on to conquer Egypt, so that the pharoahs were now controlled by Persia."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607335Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8906-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By 490 BCE, a king named Darius ruled over the Persian Empire, adding to it with territory in the Indus Valley."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607342Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8906-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Darius wanted to add the Greek city-states to his empire and so the two civilisations went to war."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607349Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9577-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Nursing in the Second World War brought new people to Britain and helped new medical techniques to succeed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607356Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9577-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """At the Queen Victoria Hospital in East Grinstead new plastic surgery techniques were trialled on badly injured soldiers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607364Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9577-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Sister Mary Meally ran the burns ward, where she looked after badly burnt airmen who were receiving treatment."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607371Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9577-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many West African and Caribbean women travelled to, and trained as nurses in Britain during World War II."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607378Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9577-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """These included Princess Ademola, daughter of the Alake of Abeokuta, an important king in Nigeria."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607385Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9528-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The early civilisations that developed in the 'cradles of civilisation' all produced art and beautiful objects."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607393Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9528-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "They carved statues out of stone or formed them from clay."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607400Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9528-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "They made pottery and painted or pressed decorative patterns into them."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607407Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9528-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When they discovered how to mix tin and copper to make bronze, this was used to make many pieces of art."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607417Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9528-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Despite similarities in how they were made these civilisations all had their own styles of art."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607425Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8949-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Vikings first came to Britain in small raids on monasteries and these grew more frequent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607433Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8949-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Great Heathen Army came to Britain, bringing lots of Vikings who began to settle on Anglo-Saxon land."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607440Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8949-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Great Heathen Army overcame all of the Saxon kingdoms apart from Wessex, which came to be ruled by King Alfred."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607447Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8949-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Fighting back against Guthrum and the Great Heathen Army, Alfred managed to confine the Vikings to the Danelaw."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607454Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8949-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good story of how the Vikings came to settle in large parts of Britain will use knowledge from across this unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607461Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8864-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """While the Picts and Scots attacked Roman Britain by land, seaborne Germanic invaders began to attack the east coast."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607635Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8864-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Romans left Britain in 410 CE due to problems elsewhere in the empire and they could no longer maintain control."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607642Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8864-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """With no Romans to defend Britain, Angles, Saxons and Jutes increased their attacks from the sea, pouring into Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607649Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8864-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """These Germanic tribes wanted to migrate to and settle in Britain because of its rich farmland."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607657Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8864-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Anglo-Saxons were able to defeat the Britons because they were skilled and experienced warriors with fearsome weapons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607665Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9571-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In the tombs of Maya rulers, archaeologists have found decorated pots that once contained a special drink."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607672Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9571-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This hot chocolate drink was made from roasting and boiling the fruit of a plant called cacao."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607679Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9571-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Maya took care preparing hot chocolate, frothing it carefully, because they believed it was a gift from the gods."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607687Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9571-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Another crop that the Maya thought was sacred was maize; it was used to make flat pancakes called tortillas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607697Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9571-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Maya believed that the gods tried for a long time to make humans, and only succeeded when they used maize to do so."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607705Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9557-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The area of Coppergate was full of tightly packed wooden houses, some of which had adjoining workshops."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607713Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9557-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The space between these was likely filled with animal pens and toilets, making it dirty and smelly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607720Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9557-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many of York's inhabitants were craftspeople: blacksmiths, wood turners, cobblers, jewellery and comb makers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607728Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9557-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There was a large hall that belonged to the Viking king of York in which disputes would be heard and settled."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607735Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9557-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Great celebrations would also take place in the hall, with music, feasting and storytelling."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607746Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8959-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Local communities often celebrate the bravery of certain individuals who fought in the Great War."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607919Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8959-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Captain Noel Chavasse was a British doctor and Olympic athlete who fought during WWI."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607927Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8959-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "He fought at one of the most famous battles of WWI: the Battle of the Somme."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607934Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8959-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "He was awarded the Victoria Cross twice for saving the lives of other soldiers."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607941Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8959-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Awards and medals are awarded to recognise soldiers who show extreme bravery, skill and service to their country."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.607949Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8280-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Philosophy is the study of some of life’s major questions, such as ‘are humans naturally good or evil?’"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608386Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8280-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ancient Greece was home to many philosophers including Socrates, Plato and Aristotle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608394Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8280-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Socrates encouraged the Ancient Greeks to think about morality and how society should work."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608401Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8280-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """His student Plato recorded many of his ideas and his own: he was interested in how states should be governed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608408Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8280-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many of the ideas these philosophers had have continued to influence people and governments today."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608416Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8907-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The first major battle between the Greek city-states and Persia was at Marathon."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608423Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8907-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Persian army fought its way onto the beach before being repulsed; a runner was sent to declare victory in Athens."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608430Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8907-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The new Persian king Xerxes attacked Greece by land, taking days to defeat a small band of Greeks at Thermopylae."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608438Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8907-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Persians then captured Athens, destroying the temple atop the acropolis before the sea-battle of Salamis."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608449Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8907-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """At Salamis, the Persians were defeated, preventing Persia from conquering Greece."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608456Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9550-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """As the Romans were leaving Britain c.410CE, groups of people called the Angles, Saxons and Jutes began to migrate there."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608669Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9550-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "These Anglo-Saxons were pagan and polytheistic: they were not Christian."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608676Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9550-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """As they began to dominate Britain, Christianity declined in areas where they settled."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608683Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9550-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This process was probably helped by the fact that many Britons had not fully embraced Christianity under Roman rule."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608695Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9550-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """For example, at Lullingstone, a pagan shrine built before the chapel was still being used after the chapel was built."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608702Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9529-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Despite having different gods and goddesses, all of these ancient civilisations built special religious buildings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608842Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9529-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many of them, like the Shang, the Egyptians and the Indus people, offered sacrifices to their gods."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608849Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9529-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All of these civilisations produced writing about trade, religion, laws and rulers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608857Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9529-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists and historians have managed to understand this writing, apart from that of the Indus Valley civilisation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608864Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8282-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The first direct democracy started in Athens; there were three main institutions of this democratic system."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608874Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8282-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The institutions were: the Ekklesia, the Boule and the Dikasteria - these were the Assembly, the Council and the Courts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608882Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8282-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Only male Athenian citizens could vote, so many people living in Athens were not involved in this democracy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608889Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8282-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ancient Athenian democracy has left a lasting legacy in the form of modern British democracy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608900Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8282-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are similarities and differences between Ancient Athenian democracy and modern British democracy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608908Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8866-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """With the departure of the Romans and the invasion of the pagan Anglo-Saxons, Christianity had declined in Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608980Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8866-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Pope sent Augustine to convert the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms to Christianity in 597CE, starting with Aethelbert of Kent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608987Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8866-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """While the Anglo-Saxons settled in Britain, the Scots, a group from Ireland, began to settle in western Scotland."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.608994Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8866-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Irish missionaries had been converting Scotland and the north of England since the 6th century."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609001Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8866-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Two forms of Christianity existed in Britain; the Synod of Whitby ruled Roman Catholic practices would be followed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609011Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9779-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """During the war, technology changed rapidly, especially in electronics and computing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609019Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9779-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """For ordinary Britons, this led to the adoption of a wide range of household appliances as these became cheaper."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609027Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9779-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Television ownership grew quickly, with 75% of households having a TV by the 1960s, making it a common leisure activity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609038Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9779-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Other domestic appliances such as fridge-freezers, vacuum cleaners and washing machines all made domestic life easier."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609046Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9779-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The appliances gave women more time to work, but poorer families did not benefit as much as others."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609053Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8956-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """WWI was a war that took place between 1914 to 1918 and involved countries from across the globe."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609060Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8956-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It was the biggest war that had ever been fought at the time which is why it was called the Great War."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609067Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8956-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Old treaties meant that many different countries were pulled into the war at the same time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609074Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8956-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Soldiers from the British Empire fought during the Great War against Germany, Austria-Hungary and the Ottoman Empire."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609081Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8956-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Much of the fighting that British and imperial troops were involved in took place in Belgium and France."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609088Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8910-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Defeating the Persian Empire and expanding Greek control into Egypt and India were not Alexander's only achievements."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609096Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8910-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """He sliced the famous Gordian knot in two and conquered Babylon, a city the Greeks could scarcely imagine."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609103Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8910-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """He founded the great city of Alexandria in Egypt, which came to be ruled by one of his generals, Ptolemy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609110Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8910-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ptolemy and his son tried to turn Alexandria into the greatest of all Greek cities, building an incredible library."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609117Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8910-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Alexandria became a centre of learning which attracted brilliant minds like Euclid and Galen."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609124Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8946-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Viking raids increased in number throughout the 800s CE, and by 850 they had begun to make winter camps in Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609372Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8946-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 865 CE, the biggest Viking army ever to have come to Britain arrived in East Anglia: The Great Heathen Army."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609379Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8946-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By 869, the Vikings had won key battles against Northumbria and East Anglia while Mercia had bribed them not to attack."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609386Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8946-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Only Wessex, which controlled most of southern Britain, remained in resistance to the Vikings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609393Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8933-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """From Medina, Muhammad tried to unite the southern Arabian tribes under the banner of Islam."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609433Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8933-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Following successful attacks against his enemies from Mecca, a ten year truce was called and the forces of Islam grew."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609441Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8933-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Mecca was established as the religious centre of Islam, the Ka’ba becoming a focus for pilgrimage and prayer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609448Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8933-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Muhammad sent Muslim armies to exploit the Byzantine and Persian Empires, weakened by fighting one another."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609502Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8934-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By the time of Muhammad’s death in 632 CE, Muslim forces had invaded the southern parts of the Persian Empire."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609548Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8934-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They also successfully invaded Byzantine territories in Syria, Palestine and Egypt."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609555Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8934-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When Muhammad died, his successor was Abu Bakr; his Rashidun Caliphate expanded into central Asia and North Africa."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609562Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8934-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Captured cities were often treated well; in Damascus the Christian people were not hurt and allowed to worship freely."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609569Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8934-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The caliph Umar captured Jerusalem in 638 CE; it is the third holiest city to many Muslims."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609581Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8935-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Umayyad Caliphate was the second dynastic caliphate and was the largest; it ruled the last united Islamic caliphate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609589Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8935-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This empire covered the Middle East, parts of Asia as far as India, North Africa, and most of Spain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609596Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8935-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It controlled a vast network of trade routes, allowing wealth and knowledge to spread throughout Islamic civilisation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609604Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8935-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Muslim control of the trade routes from Southern Europe to East Asia, known as the Silk Roads, was very lucrative."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609611Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8279-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Trojan War was a mythical conflict between the Ancient Greeks and Troy, a city most likely in modern day Turkey."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609622Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8279-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The war began when a Trojan, Paris, kidnapped Helen from the Greek King Menelaus."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609630Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8279-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Greeks defeated the Trojans but their greatest warrior, Achilles, was killed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609637Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8279-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This myth was first written down as an epic poem called *The Iliad* by the Greek poet, Homer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609645Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8279-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """*The Iliad* not only became a major part of Ancient Greek identity, but influenced literature and art through the ages."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609652Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9570-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Maya believed the sky was where the gods lived; watching it carefully they tracked the movement of celestial bodies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609659Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9570-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Maya had lots of different calendars, some were based on these movements, others on the time it took maize to grow."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609666Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9570-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Maya used these calendars to make sure they carried out religious ceremonies at the right times and to measure time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609673Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9570-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Maya used cycles to measure time, so their calendars were circular and relied on great mathematical understanding."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609680Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9570-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Using these calendars, the Maya recorded the dates of when important things happened, using their hieroglyphic writing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609687Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9781-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Britain changed in a number of ways following the Second World War; most of these were permanent and major changes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609769Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9781-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Diversity increased with the arrival of the Windrush Generation, although many migrants faced a lot of discrimination."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609776Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9781-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Changing technology was a turning point in the lives of some women and many British households."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609783Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9781-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A great deal of social and cultural change took place with the influence of the 'Baby Boomer' generation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609791Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9781-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good explanation of why this period was a turning point in British history will use knowledge from across this unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609798Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8960-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """While men were sent to the front, the war also had an impact on those who stayed behind."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609805Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8960-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The First World War was the first total war: the activities of both soldiers and civilians contributed to it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609812Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8960-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There were shortages of food, more so in the cities, where it was harder for people to grow their own food."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609820Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8960-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Women had to work in the fields and the factories to replace the men who had left for the front."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609831Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8960-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This led to a big change in the way that women were treated and helped some women win the vote in 1918."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609839Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8915-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """After Rome's fall in 476 CE, the Byzantine Empire survived in the east, and considered themselves Romans."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609901Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8915-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Constantinople grew strong and beautiful with impressive artworks, churches and the famous hippodrome."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609909Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8915-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Emperor Justinian ruled from 527 to 565 CE."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609916Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8915-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Justinian compiled a code of law and ordered all his subjects to be Christian, and to worship in the way he told them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609923Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8915-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Eastern Church believed many of the same things as in the West, but they did not recognise the pope's supremacy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.609930Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9549-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Historians are not sure exactly when Christianity was introduced to Britain."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610010Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9549-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In the 4th century CE, after the conversion of Constantine, it became increasingly popular among the elite."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610018Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9549-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Historians know about this rise in popularity from various physical objects that have been found."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610025Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9549-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """At Hinton St Mary an early 4th century mosaic appears to show a portrait of Jesus."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610036Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9549-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """At Lullingstone, archaeologists unearthed the remains of a chapel within a Roman villa with Christian wall paintings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610044Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9776-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "At the end of the Second World War Britain was victorious but weak."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610193Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9776-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Bombing campaigns had destroyed many homes and factories in Britain's cities."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610201Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9776-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Britain was nearly bankrupt having had to spend so much money on the war."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610208Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9776-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "384 000 British soldiers had died alongside 70 000 civilians."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610215Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9776-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 1945 the British public elected a new government that promised to help Britain to recover."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610223Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8909-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In his first battle against the Persians, Alexander showed great bravery and won the respect of his soldiers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610230Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8909-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Alexander captured city after Persian city, showing the people great mercy before defeating Darius III at Issus."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610237Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8909-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Alexander then marched into Egypt, where the people made him pharaoh as thanks for ridding them of their Persian rulers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610244Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8909-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Alexander then sought out Darius III, defeating him at Gaugamela with superior tactics against the Persian chariots."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610252Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8909-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Alexander conquered Babylon before continuing east to the River Indus; he died whilst returning home with his army."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610259Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9780-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 1966 Time Magazine named London the 'Swinging City', meaning it was exciting and cool."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610389Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9780-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This was because of the large numbers of young people in London, and Britain, who were known as ‘Baby Boomers’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610396Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9780-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Wages had risen and 'Baby Boomers' had more disposable income to spend on things like fashion and music."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610404Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9780-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """New fashions such as the miniskirt and various types of bright clothing and new hairstyles became very popular."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610411Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9780-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """New 'rock and roll' music became popular. A band called ‘The Beatles’ became major stars during the 1960s."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610418Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8912-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Christianity began in the 1st Century CE when followers of Jesus Christ began to spread their new religion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610465Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8912-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Early Christianity spread from Judea throughout the Roman Empire, reaching Roman Britain in the late 2nd century CE."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610472Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8912-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """At first Christians were persecuted in the Roman Empire as their faith worried the Romans."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610480Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8912-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Christians were scapegoated and punished severely, often by being attacked and killed by wild animals in amphitheatres."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610487Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8912-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Many Christians were killed for their faith, making them martyrs."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610494Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8954-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Athelstan’s reign did not see the end of the Vikings in England, with continued raids and uprisings in Northumbria."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610502Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8954-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In 1013, Sweyn Forkbeard captured the whole of England before dying."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610509Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8954-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This left his son Canute to successfully contest the throne of England with an Anglo-Saxon, Edmund Ironside."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610516Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8954-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Canute became King of England, Norway and Denmark, creating a huge North Sea empire which English trade benefited from."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610523Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8954-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """His son Harthacnut succeeded him in 1035 and ruled for seven years until an Anglo-Saxon, Edward, took the throne."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610534Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9572-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Maya have a lot in common with other early civilisations from around the world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610696Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9572-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They farmed, built great cities and temples, had rulers, worshipped gods and wrote things down."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610703Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9572-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """However, they were also distinctive compared with other early civilisations e.g. they were a stone age society."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610711Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9572-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Maya's advanced understanding of maths and astronomy and bloodletting was very important in their religion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610718Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9572-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good description of what made the Maya both similar and different will use knowledge from across this unit"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610725Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9556-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """York, a major settlement in the Anglo-Saxon kingdom of Northumbria, was captured by the Vikings in 866 CE."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610737Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9556-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It was an important strategic location between the Ouse and Foss rivers, making it easy to defend and good for trade."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610749Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9556-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Vikings restored the old Roman walls and it quickly became the main Viking city in Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610756Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9556-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Vikings called it Jorvik, which was also the name they used for their kingdom in Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610764Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9575-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Second World War was fought across Europe, Africa, Asia, and the Middle East."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610771Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9575-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """During the war, soldiers from all over the British Empire and Commonwealth fought against Nazi Germany and their allies."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610778Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9575-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Before the war, most people in Britain would only rarely travel abroad or meet people from other countries."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610785Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9575-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """With large numbers of British soldiers mixing with Empire and Commonwealth troops this changed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610792Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9575-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Britain itself, many people travelled from across the Empire to assist the war effort, bringing ethnic diversity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610799Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8874-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Most of our sources for Anglo-Saxon Britain are artefacts, supplemented by some writing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610807Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8874-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "All of these sources can be used for different enquiries."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610814Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8874-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By using the sources in different ways, and asking different questions, historians have inferred different things."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610825Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8874-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Historians have inferred a lot about Anglo-Saxon culture and society by combining their findings from different sources."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610833Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8874-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good description of the evidence used to uncover life in Anglo-Saxon Britain will use knowledge from across this unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610840Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8873-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Historians believe that Anglo-Saxon churches were built on sites of older pagan temples and places of worship."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610848Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8873-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists have found the remains of Anglo-Saxon churches and monasteries, such as Jarrow Abbey."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610855Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8873-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """These were centres of manuscript making and learning; Bede entered one aged 7 and went on to write a history of Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610862Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8873-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Franks Casket, a 700s CE Northumbrian chest, has both pagan imagery and the Christian Adoration of the Magi."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610870Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8873-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Historians argue about what else it shows, but it does suggest pagan traditions continued after Christianity’s spread."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610877Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9576-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Second World War saw mass bombing campaigns against British civilians for the first time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610888Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9576-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Nazi Germany targeted British cities in 1940-1941, hoping to destroy British industry and morale."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610896Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9576-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The government had prepared for this by evacuating many children away from the cities the moment the war started."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610903Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9576-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """For many city children, this was the first time they had been to the countryside, seen farm animals or eaten vegetables."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610911Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9576-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """For many children, away from home for so long, returning to their old lives and families in the city was very difficult."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610918Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9566-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Whether or not the British Museum should return its Benin Bronzes has caused lots of arguments."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610966Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9566-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Nigeria argues that they should be returned because they were originally taken from Benin City without permission."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610973Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9566-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some museums have returned looted Edo artwork to Nigeria, but British law prevents the British Museum from doing so."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610981Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9566-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In the USA, descendants of West African enslaved people are trying to stop the return of Edo artwork to Nigeria."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610988Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9566-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This is because some of the art was made using metals that were traded by Europeans for enslaved people."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.610995Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8952-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """After her husband’s death in 911, Aethelflaed worked with her brother Edward, King of Wessex to attack the Vikings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611043Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8952-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """She captured Tamworth, Mercia’s old capital, and used it as a base from which to drive back the Vikings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611051Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8952-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """At the same time, her brother Edward won numerous victories against the Vikings in East Anglia."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611058Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8952-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 917 Aethelflaed launched an assault on the Viking town of Derby, capturing it, followed by Leicester soon after."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611069Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8952-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """On the eve of Aethelflaed's death in 918, only York remained as a Viking stronghold."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611077Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8951-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """After Alfred’s treaty with Guthrum, he controlled much of Mercia but made himself their overlord instead of their king."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611084Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8951-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Alfred married his daughter, Aethelflaed to Mercia’s most powerful man: Aethelred."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611091Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8951-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Aethelflaed was heavily involved in rebuilding Mercia following Viking occupation by building burhs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611098Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8951-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Her rule was strengthened by her piety; she built a priory at Gloucester which housed the recaptured bones of St Oswald."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611106Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8951-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By 902, her older husband was sick and Aethelflaed defeated Vikings at Chester in 907."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611113Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8869-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """One of the main sources of evidence archaeologists use to investigate the Anglo-Saxons are their grave goods."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611190Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8869-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Sutton Hoo burial mound was discovered in East Anglia in 1938; it contained the grave goods of an Anglo-Saxon king."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611197Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8869-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Intricate gold and bronze jewellery has helped archaeologists to understand that the Anglo-Saxons were skilled artisans."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611204Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8869-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some pieces contain garnets that probably came from as far away as India; silver plates and bowls were from Byzantium."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611212Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8869-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A beautiful bronze helmet, a sword and the remains of a boat show how important warfare was to Anglo-Saxon culture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611219Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8863-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 367 CE, the Scots from Ireland and Picts from Scotland came together to attack Roman Britain but were defeated."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611226Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8863-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 401 CE, the last Roman legionaries left Hadrian’s Wall, built over 200 years before to protect the northern frontier."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611233Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8863-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Much of south-east England and the Midlands had a Romano-British culture."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611240Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8863-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Wales and the north and south-west of England had less Romanisation."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611248Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8863-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Scotland was mostly controlled by the Celtic Picts."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611255Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8948-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By 875 Guthrum began to attack Wessex once again, almost capturing Alfred at Chippenham in January 878."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611403Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8948-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Alfred raised as many soldiers as possible from across Wessex and defeated Guthrum at the Battle of Edington in May 878."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611410Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8948-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """After the battle Alfred allowed Guthrum to rule the Viking dominated area known as the Danelaw."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611418Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8948-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Danelaw was north of a line between the Thames to and Mersey, including East Anglia, Northumbria and some of Mercia."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611425Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8948-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """As part of the peace agreement Guthrum agreed to convert to Christianity, with Alfred as his godfather."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611432Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9537-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 1976 the archaeologist Zheng Zhenxiang made an amazing discovery at a dig in eastern China."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611443Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9537-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "She uncovered a royal tomb, filled with jade, bone and bronze artefacts."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611451Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9537-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The tomb also contained the bodies of six dogs and sixteen enslaved people."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611458Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9537-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Zhenxiang and her team identified the tomb as belonging to Fu Hao, a queen and general of the Shang Dynasty."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611465Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4623-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Various major problems affected the Western Roman Empire after its split, leading to many theories about its fall."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611473Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4623-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Western Roman Empire had many financial, political and military problems after the Empire’s division."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611480Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4623-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Western Roman Empire was almost destroyed when Alaric and the Visigoths attacked Rome in 410 CE."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611488Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4623-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Western Roman Empire collapsed in 476 CE when Germanic tribes defeated the last Western Roman Emperor."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611498Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9559-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """At Coppergate, archaeologists found a metal padlock and key, which suggests the owner was rich."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611573Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9559-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Whoever owned them would have controlled access to the home and to valuables that were locked away."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611580Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9559-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They also found 42 pairs of ice skates, made from horse or cattle leg bones, and used for transportation and leisure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611588Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9559-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A discovered wooden gaming board with walrus ivory pieces tells us that the Vikings liked to play boardgames."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611596Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9559-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A discovered coin die with a design referencing St Peter and Thor shows how religious beliefs blended in Viking York."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611603Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8942-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cordoba was part of Al Andalus, Muslim Spain, when it was captured by the exiled Umayyad prince Abd al-Rahman."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611721Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8942-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Although ruled by the Abbasid’s rivals, Cordoba had many similarities to Baghdad."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611728Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8942-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It was a centre for art and learning, known for its jewellery made from Chinese jade as well as its great colleges."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611736Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8942-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Christian and Jewish scholars were encouraged to visit Baghdad; in Cordoba Christians and Jews worshipped freely."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611743Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8942-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cordoba’s mosques mirrored Visigothic, Roman and Syrian styles, in contrast with Baghdad’s Persian influences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611750Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9561-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """For almost 125 years roughly 5,000 bronze artifacts have been exhibited in museums across the world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611758Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9561-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They were produced in the historic West African Kingdom of Benin which was located in what is now Nigeria."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611765Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9561-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In the British Museum in London there are hundreds of these objects."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611776Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9561-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 2021 the British Museum received a request from Nigeria to return the bronzes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611787Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9561-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """So far, the British Museum has not returned the bronzes, which has caused lots of arguments."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611795Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8283-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Ancient Greek language has had a great influence on English and other languages."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611839Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8283-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Greek alphabet has some similarities with the English alphabet; many English words have Greek prefixes or suffixes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611846Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8283-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Ancient Greeks built grand buildings with distinctive features such as columns, friezes and ceremonial gateways."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611853Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8283-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many of these features are still seen in buildings today, showing that Ancient Greek architecture still has influence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611864Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9553-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The strength of Christianity in Ireland led to its own missionary activity, and Irish missionaries travelled widely."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611934Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9553-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """St Columba was one of these, and travelled to the Scottish island of Iona in the late 6th century to set up a monastery."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611941Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9553-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """From Iona, St Columba spread Christianity through the Pictish territories of Western and Northern Scotland."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611948Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9553-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """St Columbanus went to Gaul at the end of the 6th century and founded two monasteries before travelling across Europe."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611955Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8943-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Baghdad, and the wider Islamic world, was connected to both Asia and Europe by trade, communication and ideas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611962Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8943-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Baghdad was built on the Abbasids’ wealth from the Silk Road and added to it through trade from East to West."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611970Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8943-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Baghdad was connected to the historic Greek and Persian dominance of the region through science and architecture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611977Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8943-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Caliph’s sponsorship of the sciences and the arts meant that Baghdad both imported and exported classical knowledge."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611984Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8943-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Baghdad’s House of Wisdom and its universities made it a centre of scientific discovery and engineering prowess."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.611991Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8938-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The major empires of Europe and Asia were: the Tang, the Abbasids, the Carolingians, the Byzantines, the Umayyads."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.612028Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8938-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In England, the Anglo Saxons were beginning to become one single kingdom."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.612035Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8938-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In Spain, the Abbasid’s Muslim enemies the Umayyads were seeking to expand north into Charlemagne’s Carolingian Empire."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.612042Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8938-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Charlemagne and Al-Rashid, caliph of the Abbasids and ruler of Baghdad, both had growing tension with the Byzantines."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.612053Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8938-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 801CE, Al-Rashid sent gifts to Charlemagne including an elephant and an automatic water clock."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.612061Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8872-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """One of the types of written sources we have from the Anglo-Saxon period are law codes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.612104Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8872-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The laws concern compensation for injuries people caused each other, suggesting Anglo-Saxon society could be violent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.612112Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8872-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Compensation differed according to status; the laws set out a strict hierarchy with enslaved people at the bottom."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.612120Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8872-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Unlike men women couldn’t receive compensation but they could own property as some laws mention inheritance for widows."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.612127Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8872-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By looking at who is mentioned and how the law affected them, historians have inferred a lot about Anglo-Saxon society."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.612134Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9555-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 1972, builders constructing a new shopping centre in the Coppergate area of York made a discovery."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.612281Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9555-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They were beginning to dig up huge amounts of Viking objects in the ground below the streets of York."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.612288Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9555-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists were called in to investigate further and soon made startling discoveries about Viking York."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.612295Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9555-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They discovered layers of moist and peaty soil that had preserved various organic remains which normally rot away."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.612303Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9555-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They found buildings, textiles, leather, seeds and other things that have given clues about life in Viking York."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.612310Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8870-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The graves of Anglo-Saxon women have provided various objects that provide clues about their lives and status."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614628Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8870-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """One Anglo-Saxon woman's grave in Canterbury seems to be of a high status woman as it contained lots of fine jewellery."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614634Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8870-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A brooch of foreign silver and garnet, likely to be a gift from the Kentish king, shows women could hold high status."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614641Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8870-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Girdle-hangers have been found, imitating keys or latch-lifters, suggesting women controlled access to the home."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614648Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8870-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Alongside domestic goods in female graves, they seem to symbolise the idea that women controlled access to the home."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614655Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9538-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Shang Dynasty began c.1600 BCE in the Yellow River Valley, later than the other major ancient civilisations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616652Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9538-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Like in Mesopotamia and Egypt, the Shang exploited the fertile land they lived in for extensive agriculture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616659Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9538-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Like in Mesopotamia and Egypt, the Shang built major cities including Anyang and Zhengzhou."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616665Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9538-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Much like the Ancient Egyptians, bronze weaponry helped the Shang to build and maintain an empire."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616672Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9540-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Shang Dynasty created the first form of Chinese writing in which characters were used to represent words and ideas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.617680Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9540-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The most detailed examples of this writing exist on oracle bones because they have survived longer than silk or bamboo."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.617687Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9540-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Questions were carved into them and then the bones were heated, causing cracks which diviners would interpret."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.617693Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9540-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Oracle bones were carved with questions about many subjects such as the weather, harvests, and Shang Dynasty rulers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.617699Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9540-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The oracle bones have provided a wealth of evidence for historians about many aspects of the Shang Dynasty."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.617705Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9532-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Following Harappa's discovery in 1921, another major site was excavated in 1922 at Mohenjo-Daro."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621262Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9532-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They uncovered huge numbers of clay seals, covered in writing and images, along with many pieces of broken pottery."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621268Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9532-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They also discovered large stone circles on which they think the Indus people threshed their crops."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621278Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9532-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They also found whistles and figures of dancing women as well as clay toys and figurines."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621284Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9532-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """From these discoveries archaeologists have worked out that the Indus Valley Civilisation was very large and complex."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621290Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8944-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The attack on Lindisfarne (where Bede had once lived) in 793 CE was the first major Viking raid on the British Isles."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.651946Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8944-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Vikings attacked using longboats crewed by about 30 warriors who could land, attack, and leave quickly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.651951Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8944-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Priories like those in Lindisfarne were centres of manuscript production and filled with valuable religious objects."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.651955Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8944-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Vikings murdered monks and stole these objects for trade and their own wealth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.651962Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9522-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Ancient Egyptians believed in many gods; one of these was Anubis, who guided the souls of the dead to the afterlife."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.652185Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9522-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Ancient Egyptians believed that when they died they would go to the afterlife if they had pleased the gods."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.652190Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9522-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They believed that everybody had a soul, and that when somone was dead, their soul returned to their body each night."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.652194Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9522-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This led them to try and preserve dead bodies with linen and by drying them in sand but with only partial success."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.652199Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9522-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By the end of the Old Kingdom they had started to embalm and mummify the bodies, placing the organs in canopic jars."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.652204Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8252-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Natural climate change has meant that different groups of humans have come to and left Britain at different times."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.658969Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8252-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Stone tools and footprints at Happisburgh show that the first known Britons came to Britain  c. 950,000 years ago."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.659005Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8252-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Around 500,000 years ago teeth and bones found at Boxgrove show Homo heidelbergensis lived in Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.659010Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8252-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ice Ages around 450,000 and 20,000 years ago resulted in long periods when no humans lived in Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.659015Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8252-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Homo sapiens came to Britain c. 40,000 years ago, left during the most recent Ice Age and returned c. 12,000 years ago."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.659021Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8254-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Dating different human remains suggests the presence of modern humans in Britain has been brief and sporadic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.680554Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8254-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It has only become continuous at the end of the last Ice Age, c.12,000 years ago."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.680561Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8254-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The modern humans who appeared in Britain were highly adaptable hunter-gatherers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.680566Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8254-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Flints found far from where they were acquired show that they moved around Britain far more than the Neanderthals had."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.680570Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8253-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Paleolithic Era took place between two million years ago and ten thousand years ago."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.684751Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8253-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Many of the types of Paleolithic human who lived in Britain used stone tools, which were often made of flint."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.684756Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8253-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """These tools, especially hand axes, are some of the main sources of evidence archaeologists have for this period."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.684760Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8253-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists have worked out how Paleolithic humans might have used their hand axes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.684765Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8253-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists think that they probably used them to skin animals for clothing and strip branches for fire and shelter."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.684769Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8257-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists have discovered many different artefacts from across the Stone Age."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.688017Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8257-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The types of artefacts found show the changes that have taken place throughout the period."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.688021Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8257-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Generally, archaeologists have found more artefacts from the more recent parts of the Stone Age."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.688026Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8257-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Different types of artefacts can be dated to different parts of the Stone Age."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.688031Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9541-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists have used the Shang Dynasty's jade artefacts to try to understand their lives."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.709351Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9541-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Jade is too hard to be carved and instead must be worn away, taking great skill and patience."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.709356Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9541-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The large number of ornamental jade weapons found suggests how important warfare was to the Shang Dynasty."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.709360Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9541-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Shang Dynasty made many real and imaginary animal figurines out of jade, including the mythical taotie."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.709365Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9541-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Mingqi are jade figures of servants, which were buried in the tombs of the wealthy to serve them in the afterlife."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.709371Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4616-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """CE and BCE are a common method used in the West to note the periods of time before and after the year ‘1’."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.713854Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4616-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Romans believed the myth that Rome was founded by Romulus."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.713859Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4616-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Romulus was raised by a wolf alongside his brother, who he later fought and killed, becoming the first King of Rome."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.713864Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4616-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This myth was important to Romans: it showed that to be Roman was to be strong and powerful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.713868Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4622-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Emperor Diocletian thought that the Roman Empire had too many problems and that it should be split in two."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.713965Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4622-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Emperor Constantine fought to reunite the empire; he created a new capital called Constantinople in 330 CE."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.713969Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4622-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The reunited Roman Empire was only temporary and it separated permanently in 395 CE."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.713974Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4622-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Western Roman Empire fell in 476 CE; the Eastern Roman Empire became the Byzantine Empire."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.713981Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4622-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Byzantine Empire was still thought of as Roman but over time the culture and traditions changed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.713986Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9547-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By examining the bones of the warrior woman buried with the Wetwang chariot archaeologists think she came from Gaul."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714077Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9547-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This has led them to understand that Celtic Britain had connections to mainland Europe during the Iron Age."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714084Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9547-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists have found other evidence to support this, such as golden coins that were minted in France and Belgium."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714093Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9547-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Evidence from the east of England shows that a leader called Cunobelin imported luxury goods from the Roman Empire."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714098Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9547-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Cunobelin even minted his own coins in the style of Roman ones, showing that these were familiar to Celtic Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714102Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4618-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Roman Republic continued to expand, conquering places like Ptolemaic Egypt."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714277Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4618-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Julius Caesar rose to power as a general and then as dictator of Rome, but was murdered by jealous senators in 44BCE."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714282Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4618-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Augustus was victorious in the subsequent civil war and became Rome's first emperor."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714287Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4618-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The empire retained a senate which awarded the emperors their power."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714294Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-4618-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Roman Empire expanded under the emperors as they used conquest to legitimise their rule."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714298Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9548-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists and historians have learnt a lot about Iron Age Britain from the artefacts that have been found."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714489Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9548-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """They have used these artefacts alongside other sources, such as Roman writing about Iron Age Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714494Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9548-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By using these sources together they have been able to piece together what Iron Age Britain was like."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714499Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9548-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Historians and archaeologists rarely rely on just one source, they often try to use lots together."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714503Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9548-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good explanation of what historians have learnt about Iron Age Britain will focus on how sources have been used."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714507Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9545-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The bones of the person buried with the Wetwang chariot have led archaeologists to think she was a woman."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714720Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9545-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The care taken to bury her, her chariot and other goods (a mirror and a brooch) suggest she was very important."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714725Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9545-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This has led them to believe that women could be powerful warriors and rulers in the Iron Age, just like men."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714729Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9545-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Later on, Ancient Roman writers also noted this, describing how women fought alongside men."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714736Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9545-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Historians think that Celtic women could become rulers in their own right and own and inherit their own land."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714741Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8255-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Mesolithic Era began around 12,000 years ago."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714812Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8255-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Britain was attached to the mainland but sea levels rose making it an island, reducing contact with the rest of Europe."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714816Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8255-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The first evidence for houses in Britain and Ireland comes from the Mesolithic Era; a lot of evidence is from campsites."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714821Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8255-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Mesolithic people hunted wild animals, fished and gathered wild plants, likely moving camps in different seasons."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714827Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8255-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Howick house is called ‘Britain’s oldest house’ with its remains suggesting it was built c.7600 years ago."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714832Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9544-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Iron Age Britain was dominated by a group of people called the Celts, who had spread across Europe."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714959Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9544-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Art was very important to the Celts, who made large numbers of metal objects in a style known as La Tène."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714966Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9544-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Snettisham Great Torc shows the incredible artistry and craftsmanship the Celts were capable of."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714973Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9544-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Battersea Shield made of bronze shows incredible craftmanship and the distinctive swirling patterns of La Tène."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714978Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9544-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists have worked out that it was too thin for protection, and so was probably an offering to the gods."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.714982Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9539-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """One reason why we know so much about the Shang Dynasty is because of their use of bronze."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715004Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9539-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Bronze dings were highly important to the Shang Dynasty."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715009Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9539-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The large size of many dings has led archaeologists to believe they were used to offer sacrifices to gods and ancestors."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715013Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9539-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the ancestors of a family were pleased, life for that family would be prosperous."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715018Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9539-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Dings required complicated moulds to produce. Wealthy Shang Dynasty used them to demonstrate their status."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715022Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8263-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Settlements were often very different e.g. Bronze Age farming communities vs Iron Age hillforts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715201Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8263-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Wattle and daub roundhouses occurred in both; farming tools were used in both but were more effective in the Iron Age."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715206Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8263-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Art styles changed from the Bronze Age to the Iron Age but metalworking was important in both periods."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715210Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8263-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Conflict between groups of people seems to have become more common in the Iron Age as distinct tribes developed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715217Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8263-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good description of the similarities and differences will use knowledge from across this unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.715224Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9542-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Shang were accomplished in using jade and bronze to create art, weapons and other objects."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.725598Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9542-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Fu Hao's tomb has shown archaeologists that women could rise to positions of power."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.725603Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9542-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Shang bronze dings and oracle bones show how they worshipped their ancestors."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.725607Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9542-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists also know lots about the Shang because of all the writing found on oracle bones."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.725614Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9542-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good explanation of the things archaelogists have found out about the Shang will use knowledge from across this unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.725618Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9531-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In 1921 an archaeological dig began at a place called Harappa on the banks of the River Indus."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.726733Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9531-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """As the archaeologists excavated they began to find  evidence of an ancient civilisation in the Indus Valley."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.726738Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9531-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Indus is a powerful river that flows through India and Pakistan."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.726742Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9531-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Just like the Nile, the Euphrates and the Tigris, the Indus floods, making the land around it very fertile."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.726746Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9531-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """About 8,000 years ago the people of the Indus Valley began to farm this land, and got better and better at it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.726751Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8268-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Sparta was very different to Athens. Sparta conquered nearby Messenia to gain farmland."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.727589Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8268-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Sparta’s government was a council of 30 men: 28 elders who limited the power of two kings, who led the army."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.727594Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8268-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Between 431-404 BCE Sparta fought the Peloponnesian War against Athens to win power over Greece, with Sparta winning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.727598Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8268-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Women and enslaved people did all the rest of the work; women could own land but could not vote."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.727603Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8268-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Spartan culture was militaristic; boys left home at an early age to train for the army which they only left aged 60."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.727607Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9536-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists have uncovered all sorts of objects that tell us about the great cities of this farming civilisation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.731103Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9536-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists have asked lots of questions about the objects to try and work things out about these people."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.731114Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9536-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """From these questions about the objects, they have found out lots of things about these people and their cities."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.731119Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9536-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """However, there are still many mysteries about these people because archaeologists cannot understand their writing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.731123Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9536-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good explanation of what archaeologists think they know about this subject will use knowledge from across this unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.731129Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8266-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ancient Greece was in the eastern Mediterranean and at its peak spread to other parts of Europe, Africa and Asia."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.735797Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8266-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Greece is mountainous with thousands of islands, leading to many smaller states making up Ancient Greece."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.735801Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8266-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The Ancient Greek civilisation began c. 900 BCE and lasted until roughly 31 BCE."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.735804Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8266-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By 750 BCE, it had colonies in Italy and Sicily but the decline of Ancient Greece coincided with the rise of the Romans."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.735810Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8266-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ancient Greek civilisation developed after the Sumerian, Egyptian, Indus and Shang civilisations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.735814Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9533-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The objects found at Harappa and Mohenjo-Daro were found in the remains of great cities built out of clay bricks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.737890Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9533-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """As the people of the Indus Valley grew better at farming, they could grow more food and some people could do other jobs."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.737894Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9533-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """People like merchants and artisans lived in these cities, which were carefully planned and laid out."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.737898Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9533-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Public baths have been found at Mohenjo-Daro and even bathrooms and toilets in people's houses in Lothal."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.737902Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9533-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All over these cities were wells for fresh water along with channels and drains to carry away sewage."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.737906Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9535-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Archaeologists do not understand everything about the Indus Valley civilisation because we cannot read their writing."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.746970Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9535-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There is no evidence of how these places were ruled or governed, but they were clearly very well organised."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.746974Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9535-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Their religion is a mystery to us, although they made lots of figurines that may have been offered to gods."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.746978Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9535-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are pictures of figures with horns or controlling animals, which historians know other Asian people believed in."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.746982Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9535-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are buildings that archaeologists thought were granaries, but now aren't sure because no grain has been found."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.746986Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8270-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ancient Greece was made up of many city-states (polises) like Athens, Sparta and Corinth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.746990Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8270-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """All the Greek polises spoke the same language and worshipped the same gods; they had a shared culture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.746994Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8270-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Although all polises were different, they had some similarities such as the agora, a big marketplace."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.746997Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8270-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In each polis, a temple was built at the highest point of the city (the acropolis)."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747001Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8270-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Each polis also had a gymnasium for men to exercise in, and a theatre where plays were performed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747005Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9534-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The people of the Indus Valley civilisation produced lots of highly decorated objects and art."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747146Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9534-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The seals that they produced had beautiful pictures of different animals including oxen and even imaginary animals!"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747150Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9534-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """These seals often had holes on the back of them and archaeologists think this could have been to hang them on a string."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747154Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9534-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """These people made beautiful jewellery out of carnelian, gold and other precious materials."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747158Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-9534-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Some of this jewellery has been found in Mesopotamia, showing that the Indus people must have traded there."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747164Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8945-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Vikings also began to raid monasteries in Ireland, founding Dublin in the 9th century."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747168Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8945-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The Norse were seafarers who travelled and settled widely across Europe, as far away as Byzantium."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747172Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8945-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In the 9th century, they settled in Iceland, and in the 10th century Erik the Red is said to have reached Greenland."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747176Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8945-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Erik’s oldest son, Leif Erikson, travelled as far as North America, calling the land he discovered Vinland."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747180Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8271-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Ancient Greece was a varied collection of different city-states and people with many differences between them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749961Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8271-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """However, there were many similarities in their culture e.g. common myths, religion, the existence of enslaved people."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749965Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8271-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Historians try to make generalisations about the places and people they investigate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749969Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8271-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Historians cannot always include everything they know about a place or a people in their accounts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749973Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8271-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A good explanation of what best represents what Ancient Greece was like will use knowledge from across this unit."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749977Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

